{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600111"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:01:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:01:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15605"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15605"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.38,0.29,0.13,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8296"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66646"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8296"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52099"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7005"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20026"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20028"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22238"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66646"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA microscopic image from a thyroid gland biopsy is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following thyroid lesions is most likely represented in this image?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anaplastic carcinoma","Follicular adenoma","Follicular carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe microscopic features described are pathognomonic for \u003Cstrong\u003Epapillary carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the thyroid. The characteristic nuclear features include ground glass (optically clear) nuclei, nuclear grooves, and intranuclear inclusions (Orphan Annie nuclei). The branching papillary architecture with fibrovascular cores is also typical, though not required for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaplastic carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows marked cellular pleomorphism and nuclear atypia with frequent mitoses. \u003Cstrong\u003EMedullary carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates a solid or nested growth pattern with amyloid deposits. \u003Cstrong\u003EFollicular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Efollicular adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E both show follicular architecture without the distinctive nuclear features of papillary carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Papillary thyroid carcinoma is characterized by distinctive nuclear features including ground glass appearance, nuclear grooves, and intranuclear inclusions (Orphan Annie nuclei).","Papillary architecture with fibrovascular cores is a hallmark of papillary thyroid carcinoma.","Nuclear features, not papillary architecture alone, are diagnostic of papillary thyroid carcinoma."],"references":["\u0022Thyroid papillary carcinoma histopathology (2)\u0022 by KGH is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Thyroid_papillary_carcinoma_histopathology_(2).jpg","Shah JP. Thyroid carcinoma: epidemiology, histology, and diagnosis. Clin Adv Hematol Oncol. 2015 Apr;13(4 Suppl 4):3-6. PMID: 26430868; PMCID: PMC5526593","Kitahara CM, Schneider AB. Epidemiology of Thyroid Cancer. Cancer Epidemiol Biomarkers Prev. 2022 Jul 1;31(7):1284-1297. doi: 10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-21-1440. PMID: 35775227; PMCID: PMC9473679"